  <main>

    <a href="/reading/natural-breadcrumbs/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">← back to index</a>

    <h1>Partial Markov Categories</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Elena Di Lavore, Mario Román, Paweł Sobociński · 2025 · <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2502.03477"><img src="/reading/arxiv.webp" alt="arxiv" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/> arXiv:2502.03477</a></p>

    <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mb-6">Prereqs: <a href="/reading/natural-breadcrumbs/fritz-2020/">🍞 Fritz 2020</a> (Markov categories). <a href="/reading/natural-breadcrumbs/staton-2025/">🍞 Staton 2025</a> (Hoare logic) helps.</p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">Not every computation succeeds. A <strong>partial Markov category</strong> extends Fritz's Markov categories with <strong>restriction</strong>: morphisms can fail, observations can have zero probability, and Bayes' theorem handles the conditioning. The framework unifies <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Judea_Pearl"><img src="/reading/wikipedia.svg" alt="wp" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/>Pearl</a>'s conditioning with <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_kinematics"><img src="/reading/wikipedia.svg" alt="wp" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/>Jeffrey's updating</a>.</p>
    </div>

    <h3>Restriction — morphisms that can fail</h3>
    <p>A <a href="https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/restriction+category">restriction category (nLab)</a> gives each morphism a "domain of definition," a partial identity marking where the morphism is defined. In probabilistic terms: some observations have zero probability, and conditioning on them is undefined.</p>

    <!-- SVG: Partial morphism — success and failure paths -->
